> It's just that export default specifically implies an evaluation of its right side, while other export forms don't.

(I apologize in advance for my terrible habit of replying with far too much detail. It's hard to break!)

Not quite sure what this is saying, since in JS declarations are evaluated, but I'm going to assume you mean it implies an expression? Otherwise you are excluding all type exports :)

From my understanding, essentially there are four kinds of export in plain JS:

```js
// 1. export name list
const foo = 123, bar = "abc";
export { foo, bar as baz };

// 2. export declaration
export function f() {}
export class C {}
export const x = 123;
// equivalent to
function f() {}
class C {}
const x = 123;
export { f, C, x };

// 3. export default expression
export default 123;
// equivalent to
const _new_name = 123;
export { _new_name as default };

// 4. export default declaration
export default function g() {}
// or
export default class D() {}
// equivalent to
function g() {}
export { g as default };
// or
class D() {}
export { D as default };
```

Note that 2, 3 and 4 are all equivalent to 1.

Typescript originally added:

```ts
// 5. export type names in name lists
type T = number;
interface U { x: number; }
export { T, U as V }

// 6. export type declarations
export type W = number;
export interface X { x: number };
```

So 5 is the type version of 1, making type and value names comparable, and 6 is the type version of 2, making type and value declarations comparable. A type version of 3 runs into syntax issues:

```ts
// 7. can't export type expression
export default { x: number }; // oops, this is a value
```

But a type version of 4 is pretty straightforward, and is more surprising for being missing than not:

```ts
// 8. export default type declaration
export default interface Y { x: number };
// equivalent to:
interface Y { x: number };
export { Y as default };
```

(only this supported at the moment, other forms, such as `export default type T = ...;` [look to be on track](https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/issues/3792#issuecomment-303526468))

If you are still unconvinced, for a motivating case, consider a standard practice of naming your files after their default export:

```js
// Storage.js
export default class Storage { ... }
```

Now say you split this into two implementations:

```js
// LocalStorage.js
import Storage from "./Storage";
export default class LocalStorage extends Storage { ... }
// RemoteStorage.js
import Storage from "./Storage";
export default class RemoteStorage extends Storage { ... }
```

Now you heard that types are what's cool right now so you rename all your files from .js to .ts. Later you realize that you don't need a `Storage` *class*, an interface would do fine. Naively:

```ts
// Storage.ts
export default interface Storage {}
```

Without `export default interface`, the alternatives are confusing, misleading or just ugly!

issue.body:
### Input Code
```ts
interface IEvent {
  type: string;
}

export default IEvent;
```
### Babel/Babylon Configuration (.babelrc, package.json, cli command)
<!--- If describing a bug, tell us what your babel configuration looks like -->

```js
{
  "presets": [
    ["@babel/env", {
      "targets": {
        "browsers": ["last 2 versions"],
        "node": "6"
      },
      "loose": true,
      "useBuiltIns": false
    }],
    "@babel/preset-stage-3",
    "@babel/typescript"
  ],
  "plugins": [
    ["@babel/plugin-transform-runtime", {
      "helpers": true,
      "polyfill": false,
      "regenerator": false,
      "moduleName": "@babel/runtime"
    }]
  ]
}
```

### Expected Behavior

Either:
* Not referencing (thus exporting) IEvent at all
* Or, setting IEvent to undefined/null/anything so parsing the file doesn't result in a runtime error

### Current Behavior

TS compilation results in:

```js
"use strict";

exports.__esModule = true;
exports.default = void 0;
var _default = IEvent; // <<< IEvent doesn't exist!
exports.default = _default;
```

Which results in the runtime error:
```js
Uncaught ReferenceError: IEvent is not defined
```

### Possible Solution
When stripping interfaces (or probably any non-value types), either:
* leave a placeholder value for exports
* or, detect references in exports and remove those exports

### Context
I'm using and re-exporting interfaces in my node modules' 'index.ts' file, so you can use them in other TypeScript projects, e.g.:

```ts
// index.ts
import { default as IEvent } from "./lib/IEvent";

// app.ts
import { IEvent } from "seng-event";
```

When publishing the package, the `tsc` also runs to generate `d.ts` files, which makes the code above work in a TS project (babel strips types and generates JS code, tsc generates the definitions).

**Workaround**
A workaround is to use named exports, since the faulty generated code only happens when using default exports.

```ts
export interface IEvent {
  type: string;
}
```

When using a named export, the export itself will be removed along with the interface, since it's a single statement. The (now empty) file will be imported somewhere, but will just result in an undefined value. This shouldn't matter, since Interfaces themselves are not used at runtime.

### Your Environment

| software         | version(s)
| ---------------- | -------
| Babel            |  7.0.0-beta.42
| node             | 8.9.1
| npm              | 5.5.1
| Operating System | macOS 10.13.3

### Related

Different but related to https://github.com/babel/babel/issues/7118 (where that's a syntax/parsing error, while this current issue is a runtime error)

